The start symbol is  

S → NT44 NT7  

In any derivation the first token of the generated string must come from NT44 (the left child of S).

The only productions for NT44 are  
NT44 → NT69 NT20  
NT44 → NT3  NT50  
NT44 → 't5'

So the first token that NT44 can yield is either
• 't5'  (via the direct terminal rule),  
• the first token produced by NT69, or  
• the first token produced by NT3.

NT69 has only the two terminal rules  
NT69 → 't4' | 't6'

NT3 can only expand as  
NT3 → NT89 NT31  

and NT89 has only the terminal rules  
NT89 → 't6' | 't5'

Consequently, the very first token produced by NT44 – and hence by the whole grammar – can only be t4, t5, or t6.  

The string we are asked to recognise begins with t2:

t2 t2 t1 …

Since t2 cannot be the first symbol generated by the grammar, the given string cannot be in the language of the grammar.

No

S expands to NT44 NT7, so the very first terminal of any sentence must come from NT44.

The only productions for NT44 are  
 NT44 → NT69 NT20  (first symbol t4 or t6),  
 NT44 → NT3 NT50  (first symbol t6),  
 NT44 → 't5'    (first symbol t5).

Hence every string derived from the grammar must begin with t4, t5 or t6.  
The given string begins with t3.

Therefore the string cannot be generated by this grammar.

No

In every derivation from the start symbol

S → NT44 NT7

the first terminal symbol of the generated string must come from the left-hand non-terminal NT44, because there are no ε-productions in the grammar.

NT44, however, can expand only in the following three ways:

1. NT44 → 't5'                     (first symbol = t5)
2. NT44 → NT69 NT20       (first symbol comes from NT69)
   • NT69 → 't4'         (first symbol = t4)
   • NT69 → 't6'         (first symbol = t6)
3. NT44 → NT3 NT50        (first symbol comes from NT3)
   • NT3  → NT89 NT31  (first symbol comes from NT89)
   • NT89 → 't5' or 't6'   (first symbol = t5 or t6)

Thus the very first terminal NT44 can ever generate is one of

t4, t5, or t6.

The string we are asked to recognise begins with

t0 …

Because t0 is not among {t4, t5, t6}, no derivation starting from S can produce a string whose first symbol is t0. Consequently the given string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The derivation must start with  

S → NT44 NT7  

so the word is split into a prefix produced by NT44 and a suffix produced by NT7.

Possible lengths and terminal sequences that NT44 can generate are:

1. NT44 → 't5'                           → [t5]  
2. NT44 → NT69 NT20 → ('t4'|'t6') 't2'  → [t4 t2] or [t6 t2]  
3. NT44 → NT3 NT50 → NT89 NT31 't3'  
   NT89 → 't6' | 't5', NT31 → 't3'      → [t6 t3 t3] or [t5 t3 t3]

Hence the first 1, 2 or 3 symbols of the string must be one of  
t5 | t4 t2 | t6 t2 | t6 t3 t3 | t5 t3 t3.

The given string begins with  

t6 t5 t5 …

No possible NT44 prefix matches t6 t5…; therefore NT44 cannot generate the required prefix, and consequently S cannot generate the whole string.

Thus the string is not in the language.

No
